explanation:
OS_CHECK_POINTER: This macro/inline must be examined to know its exact expansion and side-effects (e.g. does it return from the function, abort, log, or modify memory). If it causes an early return or writes/clears data, that can make subsequent operations redundant or unreachable and affect dead-code determination.

OS_CHECK_SIZE: Same rationale as OS_CHECK_POINTER — its expansion may perform validation, logging, early returns, or other side effects that change whether later operations are ever executed or are redundant.

OS_NetworkGetHostName_Impl: The low-level implementation is the primary producer of host_name and the return_code. You must know whether it always (or sometimes) writes/clears host_name on failure or success. If the Impl already guarantees host_name[0]=0 on failure, the explicit assignment in the target function would be redundant (dead) and vice versa.

OS_SUCCESS: The definition/value and semantics of this success code are required to evaluate the if (return_code != OS_SUCCESS) test. Knowing all possible return codes of the Impl is necessary to decide whether the conditional assignment is ever executed and whether it affects behavior.

OS_printf: The static call graph shows this function as a callee (likely used inside the CHECK macros). If logging calls occur inside the checks, those I/O side-effects are part of program behaviour; their presence/absence affects whether removed code would change observable behaviour (i.e. not dead).

UT_Stub_RegisterReturnType, UT_Stub_RegisterContextWithMetaData, UT_ExecuteBasicHandler, UT_Stub_GetReturnValuePtr: These unit-test/stub-framework symbols appear in the static call graph as callees (they may be invoked by the CHECK macros or stubs in test builds). Their behavior (e.g. forcing returns, setting return values, logging, modifying buffers) can alter control flow or side-effects relevant to deciding if any executed operation in this function is redundant. Include them to cover test-harness variations of the CHECK/Impl behavior.
